text=(:title Attacking from the Back of a Napkin:)%0aThis article discusses how to run a fairly efficient attack without%0arelying on a [[battle calculator]] (link to a few battle calculators). The first section describes how to%0aattack in waves. The second section provides a couple rules of thumb%0athat help calculate how many units to bring.%0a%0aBeyond the rule-of-thumb approach highlighted below, you can always%0amanually calculate your attack. First, calculate the total power of both%0asides. When calculating the value of base defenses, remember to multiply%0athe power by the number of turrets or rings (those multiples of five).%0aAdjust for the presence of Command Centers to the appropriate party.%0a%0a(:*toc:)%0a%0a[[!Guides]]%0a%0aAttack in Waves%0a===============%0a%0aFirst, you should always consider attacking in waves. Never hurry an%0aattack if you can avoid it. The great thing about being in the attack is%0athat initiative should be yours. Therefore, you should time the attack%0ato advantage you---so take your time. If you're on the defense, then it%0ais more likely you are being attacked by overwhelming force. Better to%0aretreat and batter elsewhere than be battered by an attacker.%0a%0aFigther Waves%0a-------------%0a%0aThe first waves should be massive Fighter drops. The goal is to kill all%0athe support fleet (i.e., unshielded fleet) in one go. How many Fighters%0ayou bring should be based on the rule of thumb listed below. If the%0afirst wave was insufficient to waste all but a handful of support ships,%0athen launch a second wave of Figthers to finish the job.%0a%0aHeavy Bomber Waves%0a------------------%0a%0aOnce the Fighters have killed all but a few unshielded units, time to%0amop up with Heavy Bombers and other escort-killing units. If you read%0aabout [[Small Fleet Doctrine]], you will know that Fighters are%0aefficient against all unshielded %0aunits.(:footnote Look at the [[new fighter rule analysis]], Fighters were once efficient against all units.:)%0aNow that your Fighter drop has%0aeliminated hostile Fighters, its time to focus on the Escort Ships. %0a%0aThe [[Small Fleet Doctrine]] says that Cruisers are efficient against%0aall Escort Ships. However, Heavy Bombers, Destroyers and Frigates are%0afairly efficient against Cruisers and Heavy Cruisers. So, use the rule%0aof thumb below to estimate how many you will need to wipe out your%0aenemy's Cruisers and Heavy Cruisers. As with Fighter waves, you may have%0aunder-estimated how many you need. Hit the enemy with a second HB wave%0auntil there are only BBs and up.%0a%0aEscort Waves%0a------------%0a%0aBy now, you should have removed all units below Battleships. If there%0aare no Titans or larger in the remaining enemy fleet, use Cruisers with%0aFighters. The Fighters absorb some of the damage that would otherwise be%0adirected at Cruisers. If there are Titans and larger, bring Heavy%0aCruisers.%0a%0aRules of Thumb%0a==============%0a%0aThis section provides a few assumptions when planning your %0aattack.(:footnote Check out my more detailed [[http://espacesociety.org/units.html|unit comparison chart]], which tries to show unit ratios needed at  ``optimal" technology levels.:)%0aRemember that these rules of thumb are just dirty-math assumptions. They%0avary with differing tech levels.%0a%0aWith FT and HB drops, you do not want to over-estimate the numbers you%0ause. Those extra units will attack higher-shielded units that are%0aunscathed by these units. That ruins your combat ratio. Remember, an%0aattack with good ratios is like fine surgery.%0a%0aFighter Drops Use the 1/2/4/6 Rule%0a----------------------------------%0a%0aThe '''1/2/4/6 Rule''' provides a guide for how many Fighters you need%0ato cleanse your enemy's fleet of escort units.  The numbers represent%0athe following assumptions:%0a%0a* 1 FT per enemy FT/BO/RC/SS%0a* 2 FT per enemy CV/HB%0a* 4 FTs per enemy DE%0a* 6 FTs per enemy FR%0a%0aRemember that the presence of other ships will destroy some of your%0aFighters. So, provide a few extra Fighters to absorb the extra damage.%0aWhat we need here is a percentage to figure the FTs that will bleed off.%0a%0aHeavy Bombers Use the 3.5/8.5 Rule%0a----------------------------------%0a%0aThe '''3.5/8.5 rule''' provides estimates for using Heavy Bombers%0aagainst Cruisers and Heavy Cruisers.  The numbers represent the%0afollowing assumptions:%0a%0a* 3.5 per enemy CR/CA%0a* 8.5 per ememy HC%0a%0aDestroyers Use the 3/7 Rule%0a---------------------------%0a%0aIf you'd rather use Destroyers against Cruisers and Heavy Cruisers, use%0athe 3/7 rule. Notice how close this rule is the the Heavy Bomber? This%0aratio should work for Frigates as well, but you have to push your%0aMissile tech. Destroyers use Plasma, which we tend to push anyway%0abecause of Cruisers.%0a%0a* 3 Destroyers per enemy CR/CA%0a* 7 Destroyers per enemy HC/FC%0a%0aCruisers and Heavy Cruisers%0a---------------------------%0a%0aCruisers yield about a 10:6 ratio against Dreadnaughts. You need about%0a30 Cruisers to kill a Dreadnought. Twenty HCs will take out a%0aDreadnought, but with a 9:8 ratio. This is less efficient. So, bring the%0aextra Cruisers.%0a%0aHeavy Cruisers yield a 2:1 kill ratio against Titans. However, you need%0a60 HCs per Titan. Bring your HCs after the Fighter and Heavy Bomber%0awaves. You will need about 200 HCs to kill a Leviathan, for a 2:1 ratio.%0a%0aThe ratios mentioned here derive from my%0a[[http://espacesociety.org/units.html|unit comparison chart]], which%0atries to show unit ratios needed at ``optimal" technology levels. The%0aactual ratios are highly dependent upon the technology of both the%0aattacker and defender.%0a%0aAttacking Massive Units%0a==================%0a%0aSay you want to target a "naked" Dread---a Dreadnought that has no escort. This is more likely to occur when there's a gullible character or some other defense (e.g. prings) in play. What I'm about to describe applies to all sorts of "massive" units. But, you don't know what to bring. All you have at your disposal are Fighters or some other small unit (e.g. Frigates). The problem is the Power of the Fighter is maybe 4, and the Dread has a Shield of 30. So, it sounds impossible.%0a%0aThe math is simpler, actually. We know that at least one percent of these smaller units pass. So, we know that 0.04 of the Fighter passes through. If you've followed my advice, you know what the Dread's Armour is (say 512). Divide that Armour value by one percent of the attacking units Power. In this case 12800. That's how many Fighters in this scenario one-shot-kill the Dread.%0a%0aThat sounds like a lot to some, perhaps. The question is: how many Fighters are killed. This is simple math as well. Just divide the Power of the Dread by the Armour of your Fighters. Assuming the Dread Power is 982, then 256 Fighters will perish in the ordeal---two percent of the 12800 Fighters.%0a%0aThis means you could go in with fewer fighters and repeat the attack. If you went in with 4200 Fighters (1/4), you'd need more than four waves. But, in the end the Dread would be dead.%0a%0aOf course, if the naked Dread has any other protection (prings), then you have to take that into account.%0a%0aLook at my [[AstroEmpires/Whither Thou Death Star]] article for more useful information on attacking massive units. %0a%0a(:comment This page has been edited using Pywe:)%0a(:title Attacking from the Back of a Napkin:)
