diff:1207416838:1207416838:=1,85d0%0a%3c This article discusses how to run a fairly efficient attack without%0a%3c relying on a battle calculator. %0a%3c %0a%3c Attack in Waves%0a%3c ===============%0a%3c %0a%3c First, you should always consider attacking in waves. Never hurry an%0a%3c attack if you can avoid it. The great thing about being in the attack is%0a%3c that initiative should be yours. Therefore, you should time the attack%0a%3c to advantage you---so take your time. If you're on the defense, then it%0a%3c is more likely you are being attacked by overwhelming force. Better to%0a%3c retreat and batter elsewhere than be battered by an attacker.%0a%3c %0a%3c Figther Waves%0a%3c -------------%0a%3c %0a%3c The first waves should be massive Fighter drops. The goal is to kill all%0a%3c the support fleet (i.e., unshielded fleet) in one go. How many Fighters%0a%3c you bring should be based on the rule of thumb listed below. If the%0a%3c first wave was insufficient to waste all but a handful of support ships,%0a%3c then launch a second wave of Figthers to finish the job.%0a%3c %0a%3c Heavy Bomber Waves%0a%3c ------------------%0a%3c %0a%3c Once the Fighters have killed all but a few unshielded units, time to%0a%3c mop up with Heavy Bombers. If you read about [[Small Fleet Doctrine]],%0a%3c you will know that Fighters are efficient against all unshielded units.%0a%3c Now that your Fighter drop has eliminated hostile Fighters, its time to%0a%3c focus on the Escort Ships. %0a%3c %0a%3c The [[Small Fleet Doctrine]] says that Cruisers are efficient against%0a%3c all Escort Ships. However, Heavy Bombers are fairly efficient against%0a%3c Cruisers and Heavy Cruisers. So, use the rule of thumb below to estimate%0a%3c how many you will need to wipe out your enemy's Cruisers and Heavy%0a%3c Cruisers. As with Fighter waves, you may have under-estimated how many%0a%3c you need. Hit the enemy with a second HB wave until there are only BBs%0a%3c and up.%0a%3c %0a%3c Escort Waves%0a%3c ------------%0a%3c %0a%3c By now, you should have removed all units below Battleships. If there%0a%3c are no Titans or larger in the remaining enemy fleet, use Cruisers with%0a%3c Fighters. The Fighters absorb some of the damage that would otherwise be%0a%3c directed at Cruisers. If there are Titans and larger, bring Heavy%0a%3c Cruisers.%0a%3c %0a%3c Rules of Thumb%0a%3c ==============%0a%3c %0a%3c Fighter Drops%0a%3c -------------%0a%3c %0a%3c as for a quick estimate for FT drops: remember the 1/2/4/6 rule:%0a%3c %0a%3c * 1 FT per enemy FT/BO/RC/SS%0a%3c * 2 FT per enemy CV/HB%0a%3c * 4 FTs per enemy DE%0a%3c * 6 FTs per enemy FR%0a%3c %0a%3c Add a few more for good luck, because some will get%0a%3c eaten by the enemy's other ships. (There may follow a%0a%3c figure on the percentage of FTs that bleed off target,%0a%3c and get absorb by other ships.)%0a%3c %0a%3c As for quick estimate of HBs to drop: remember the%0a%3c 3.5/8.5 rule:%0a%3c %0a%3c * 3.5 per enemy CR/CA%0a%3c * 8.5 per ememy HC%0a%3c %0a%3c With FT and HB drops, you do not want to over%0a%3c estimate it, and force your FTs/HBs to attack%0a%3c high shielded units that they cannot damage, or%0a%3c else you will just be wasting credits. a good%0a%3c attack with good ratios is like fine AE surgery.%0a%3c %0a%3c Also, remember, these are just quick dirty-math%0a%3c assumptions. They vary with differing tech%0a%3c levels.%0a%3c %0a%3c (:title Attacking Using the Back of a Napkin:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:comment This page has been edited using Pywe:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
